<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910422-0052</DOCNO><DOCID>910422-0052.</DOCID><HL>   Budget Deficit Narrowed   To $40.85 Billion in March</HL><DATE>04/22/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2</SO><IN>ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)U.S. ECONOMIC AND MONETARY INDICATORS (EMI)</IN><NS>ECONOMIC NEWS, TRENDS, INDEXES, PROJECTIONS, ANALYSES (ECO)ECONOMIC RELEASES (EMI)</NS><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The federal government's budget deficitnarrowed to $40.85 billion in March from $53.32 billion ayear earlier, the Treasury reported.   The budget gap was larger than February's deficit of$26.18 billion and put the deficit for the first six monthsof fiscal 1991 at $151.64 billion, a bit bigger than the$150.84 billion deficit for the first half of fiscal 1990.The deficit for all of fiscal 1990 was $220.39 billion. TheOffice of Management and Budget estimates this year's deficitwill total $318.12 billion.</LP><TEXT>   Allied contributions to Operation Desert Storm were $12.85billion in March, bringing the six-month total to $27.13billion.   Government receipts totaled $64.81 billion in March,unchanged from a year earlier and up from February's $67.66billion. The government spent $105.65 billion, compared with$118.13 billion in March 1990 and $93.83 billion in February.   Receipts for the first six months of fiscal 1991 were$482.64 billion, up from $458.19 billion a year ago. Outlayswere $634.28 billion, compared with $609.02 billion in thefirst six months of fiscal 1990.</TEXT></DOC>